{"cursor":"2439","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn statistics, and specifically in the study of the Dirichlet distribution, a\n'neutral vector' of random variables is one that exhibits a particular type of\nstatistical independence amongst its elements.  In particular, when\nelements of the random vector must add up to certain sum, then an element in the\nvector is neutral with respect to the others if the distribution of the vector\ncreated by expressing the remaining elements as proportions of their total is\nindependent of the element that was omitted.\n","linknr":116,"url":"Neutral_vector","recorded":1362543060,"links":12,"instances":[],"pdf":[],"categories":["Theory of probability distributions","Statistical terminology"],"headings":["Definition","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/f/c/4fc3e3c98d13ed389817f11dc66c10a6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/4/0/f40aec299a9f23ac07467dc660adeb70.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/f/c/4fc3e3c98d13ed389817f11dc66c10a6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/b/e/0bef594e44b2e62e9b7626086e4dd705.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/d/1/fd17d38bb8babcf75be22ace562d3e58.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/f/c/4fc3e3c98d13ed389817f11dc66c10a6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/2/6/c264bdb22a754961ef6021b6c1914161.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/2/1/02129bb861061d1a052c592e2dc6b383.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/2/6/c264bdb22a754961ef6021b6c1914161.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/2/6/c264bdb22a754961ef6021b6c1914161.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/7/8/678c79f6db633ef2b2f241f16d526cbf.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/5/5/c5550be7b87cf24698427e4bdb08d21b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/e/6/8e629f813322c8b262a580576ef27932.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/e/6/8e629f813322c8b262a580576ef27932.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/b/4/bb452069eb7210ee40d90a56f77afaf1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/ma